column1: Live Table 600:  Numbers of households on local authorities' housing waiting lists1,3,4, by district: England, 31 March2 1987-20215

column3: Lower and Single Tier Authority Data

column1: Cells highlighted in red with yellow text contain imputed data - these data should not be seen as an estimate for the individual authority but is given on an authority basis to allow custom totals to be constructed
1. Figures in this table are unaudited by local authorities. Data between 1997 and 2004 are more prone to errors as they were validated less rigorously.
2. Up to 2017-18, the reference date was 1 April rather than 31 March, e.g. under 2018, it is 1 April 2018 rather than 31 March 2018.

3. The number of households on the waiting list is not the same as the number of households waiting. Local authorities periodically review their lists to remove households who no longer require housing, so the total number of households on waiting lists may overstate the number of households who still require social housing at any one time. The frequency of reviews varies between local authorities.  Waiting list size may also be affected by other factors  for example, there is the potential for some households to be on the waiting list of more than one local authority.

4. The Localism Act 2011, which came into force in 2012, gave local authorities the power to set their own qualification criteria determining who may or may not go onto the housing waiting list. Previously, local authorities were only able to exclude from their waiting list people deemed guilty of serious unacceptable behaviour. The Localism Act changes have contributed to the decrease in the number of households on waiting lists since 2012.

5. Data on waiting lists and its predecessors started being collected in 1985. In 2021, data from 1987-1996 were reintroduced in this table as part of a data quality improvement project to give users more contextual information and a longer time series. However, these data are based on historical files based on late-1990s geography and may be more prone to errors. These data may also differ from previously published figures for waiting lists as  previous imputation or weighting was removed and they are presented consistently with current imputation rules for waiting list. Data for 1985 and 1986 are not complete enough to allow for publication.

6. From 31 March 2021 Telford & Wrekin Council does not operate a housing waiting list.  It makes nominations to local housing providers from its Nomination Pool. The Council continues to work in partnership with local housing association providers in the borough through the local Social Housing Forum.
